ular is having a very rough year. Here's a novel thought, if you're a retailer and you're closing stores due to a \"decline in performance\" that you probably invested millions to open and maintain, that's not good for your business. Considering you need your stores open to sell your overpriced bras and lingerie. Don't overthink this one. Physical retail is a dying industry and only a few will survive. Even if Victoria's Secret ultimately survives, it won't be without many battle scars.  \n\n2) The next component is more of an expansion of the previous point. I mentioned innovate or die, and it seems that Victoria's Secret is [choosing](https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/08/victorias-secret-is-retails-latest-fallen-angel.html) to die slowly. Although Victoria's Secret is still the main lingerie provider in the US for now, they have failed to adjust their business to account for the tens of millions of women who literally do not fit into their \"sexy\" products. How hard is it to simply make some shit for women of larger/various sizes? They sacrificed their business to try and cater to only the \"sexiest\" women and it is backfiring big time. Normally I'm not a big \"look at the balance sheet and other various financial metrics of companies\" type of person. I trade and invest using other tools, ideas, and metrics. But everyone please go and look at all their key financial metrics. Declining net income every year since 2016, declining total assets every year since 2016, increased liabilities every year since 2016, declining same store sales every year since 2016, etc. I mean fuck, just [look](https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/LB/chart?p=LB#%3D%3D) at what the stock has done since it's all time peak of almost $100 in 2015. Every rally besides their sizeable rally in 2017 from ~$35-$63 ended up being a great shorting opportunity if you gave yourself at least a few months. And obviously since the highs of 2017 every rally has continued to be a great shorting opportunity. This is all despite the market going to all time highs over the same period of time. To continue with the evidence of declining business for Victoria's Secret lets look at their annual fashion show. Last year was their worst year ever as far as viewership ratings for their biggest event of the year. [This](https://www.huffpost.com/entry/victorias-secret-show-cancelled_n_5d4197c1e4b0db8affb171c3) year they flat out cancelled their annual fashion show! Remember, this is their Super Bowl. Imagine if the NFL had their worst viewership ratings of the Super Bowl one year and the very next year they decided to scrap the Super Bowl entirely for the time being. The annual fashion show typically generated large amounts of buzz and positive publicity for Victoria's Secret. To me it is a major red flag that a retail company with visibly declining sales and business who is desperate to turn around sentiment doesn't host their most important event of the year. The annual fashion show gives them their biggest stage and best chance to actually turn things around and it's not happening in 2019. They seemingly can't escape bad news event after bad news event this year.  \n \n3) Speaking of bad news, it's never a good thing to have multiple [lawsuits](https://finance.yahoo.com/news/lead-plaintiff-deadline-alert-faruqi-191500020.html) against your company for potentially lying/misleading the SEC and defrauding investors. From that article \"L Brands\u2019 Victoria\u2019s Secret and PINK businesses failed to disclose their deteriorating operating performance due to, among other things, increased competition from new lingerie brands\". Now I do know that most of these types of lawsuits don't materialize into anything that affects the stock other than maybe when the news is first announced. But it's just another little piece of the pie that is in favor of the shorts. Although I personally think it's unlikely, there could be news any given day about a fine from the SEC or a forced payout to investors for their actions. Any of us who are already in position with shorts will potentially benefit immediately should these lawsuits actually materialize into a negative news event for LB.  \n \n*[Here](https://finance.yahoo.com/news/shareholder-alert-zuo-omcl-lb-134420394.html)  \n\n+[Here] (https://finance.yahoo.com/news/shareholder-notice-brodsky-smith-llc-105000074.html)  \n\n-[Here](https://finance.yahoo.com/news/shareholder-alert-claimsfiler-reminds-egbn-025000241.html) are some of the other few lawsuit updates I've seen recently.   \n\nDid you really think the bad news ended there? Their Chief Marketing Officer (CMO) who has been with the company since the early 1980's happened to [resign](https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/05/victorias-secrets-l-brands-is-losing-its-marketing-chief.html) about a week ago. Only the CEO Les Wexner has been with the company longer. When I see executives stepping down/resigning I always try to see if there is any writing on the wall about a negative environment they're trying to avoid going forward. This looks to be a textbook case of that. Company facing serious declining business? Check. Company recently cancelled their biggest event of the year? Check. Company facing multiple class action lawsuits? Check. Company CEO caught up in a potentially massive child sex trafficking scandal? Check, and we'll get much more into that soon. To me it couldn't be more obvious that this CMO sees an impossible to win environment for Victoria's Secret/LB and decided it's best to get out now before the final hammer really comes down on them.  \n \n4) The last point regarding just their business/stock price has to do with their short float % and institutional ownership. [LB] (http://shortsqueeze.com/shortinterest/stock/LB.htm) has a 6.66% short interest and a 70-75% institutional ownership. Their CEO owns about 17% of the shares himself as well. I'm not sure how familiar y'all are with short interest in retail stocks. But it is pretty much standard to see 20-40%+ short interest in any given retail stock. It hasn't been a secret for years that physical retailers are under serious threat and thus many people have the same idea to short these types of companies. But L Brands short % stands at less than 7%. This is another positive catalyst for those who are short this dying company. Everyone should be familiar with the concept of a short squeeze. The upside in a short squeeze is only magnified the greater the amount of people that are short that company. But considering L Brands has an extremely low short interest compared to most other retailers L Brands is more \"protected\" from experiencing an extreme short squeeze if unexpected good news were to drop. Although I can't foresee any positive news catalysts in the near future, they do report earnings on 8/21 after hours. Earnings reports as we all know can produce any result imaginable. We will probably see a move ranging from -30% to +30% or anything in between. Although it's hard to see LB producing a good quarter after the year they've had so far, anything is possible and I'm not a degenerate moron who is Yolo'ing on weekly options like most of /r/WSB. Now, taking a look at the 70-75% institutional ownership you can analyze it from a few different perspectives. From my perspective it is both good and bad that this stock is primarily owned by institutions. It is good for us LB bears in the sense that if any of these institutions decide to exit, LB will come down significantly since the institutions own the majority of the shares and are really the ones that control the stock price. On the other hand, institutions that have access to millions, or billions of dollars of capital may take the opposite stance as me on LB. Perhaps some analyst at these institutions may want to double or triple down on their LB position. Maybe they'll come out with a price target upgrade next month. Who knows. But those are legitimate possibilities and we have to be careful because we